Problem solving doesn't come naturally to them and actually stresses them out. They need to let their man isolate himself and not try to "interfere with his testosterone restoration process," their own well being and needs be damned. In John's perfect world, a woman lets a man do, think, act, and be however he wants while her needs are fulfilled by "nurturing him." In this world, a man comes home from work and his wife does too, she cleans the house and makes him dinner while he watches TV so he can "recharge his testosterone." author: @MikeEnRegalia
processed_text: Only one minute through, and I'm already cringing. Operatic vocals are the great enemy of music. Cursed be whoever invented that crap several centuries ago.

author: @MikeEnRegalia
processed_text: BTW: There are some instances where operatic vocals don't suck, but they're very rare. As exemplified by the abysmal performance here, it's really, really hard to get them right.

author: @JordanSmithConductor
processed_text: @Michael, it's unfortunate that these are your feelings. I do understand them because I once felt as you do. But it's difficult to believe that you have investigated the art form well enough to have such a harsh opinion. You're more than entitled to have that opinion, and you're more than welcome to investigate it and still never find it to suit your tastes. But I don't think you would be quite so harsh as to call operatic vocals, "the great enemy of music," if you knew a little more about what you were criticizing.

author: @MikeEnRegalia
processed_text: ***** Thanks for attacking me personally because I haven't reached the same conclusion as you did. Suffice it to say that I've been listening to (and making) music for more than 20 years, with a music collection of 20,000+ tracks from Alamaailman Vasarat to Frank Zappa via Gershwin, Orff, Dvorak and John Zorn, Magma and Mike Keneally. Heck, I even built my own music website with an unique tagging system which, for vocals, distinguishes between operatic and theatrical as well as growling, screaming and shouting. But what do I know.I know that operatic vocals are an established art form, but I simply don't see anything useful in them - and I have no problem pointing that out publicly, just as the little girl did in that parable about the Emperor's new clothes.And about the performance in the video: Perhaps I could begin to enjoy it if the two singers had managed to synchronize their vibrato ...

author: @JordanSmithConductor
processed_text: Michael Riess I am sorry that you feel personally attacked but nothing could be further from my intent, and I think if you review my words carefully, you'll see that this was not what was communicated. I also made a point to underscore my empathy in that, like you, I once found little to love about the style of singing used in opera. Instead, I wanted to engage you and anyone else watching in a constructive discussion, which (aside from the opening bit) I believe you've done in your response.I focused my comments not on this performance or on your credibility. Even if you were a teenager with little to go on, you'd still be entitled to your opinion, as I pointed out. All the more so considering the amount of effort you have put into amassing a healthy music library that you have catalogued! Again, I am not doubting you may have a finely cultivated taste for some or perhaps many musical genres. And to that I say bravo. But to describe operatic vocals broadly in such disparaging terms betrays a lack of familiarity with the brilliant musicians who devote their entire lives to making great music. You are more than welcome to accept that this is so and say, "sorry, not for me." And who could blame you? But you can't hope to make larger more broad claims about "the death of music," as you put it, if your intent is to make some sort of objective truth claim. If that was not your intent, then you might consider rewording it to emphasize how these are merely your opinions.I did appreciate the 2nd comment you made where you walked it back a little bit, but I find it difficult to see someone take to youtube and make such unfounded critical comments on the comment section of the video itself. (Your own personal facebook page would be one of a number of great places where you "own the space" and would be free to write whatever you like without it being linked back to the video itself). I know that it would be pretty crushing to me if someone had written something on one of my videos that so thoroughly invalidated my work, and I can't doubt that these artists and their families have seen or will see this video and probably the comments. If we were dealing with a Beyoncé video or something, fine, let'r rip. She's loaded. And she'll never have time to read everything with millions of fans. When you're that big, you're going to have haters. But not all videos on youtube are created equal. These are normal ordinary people who devote their lives to performing great music. The message: no need to be ugly.Also, I will point out that this is live, and the audio is quite clearly not rigged for musical performance. This is a conference room-esque theater that is very clearly dry as a bone and very poorly balanced by a sound engineer not used to managing something like this. This is not to mention that the mics keep peaking! While you claim to have significant knowledge about recorded music, it is clear from your criticism that you are not quite as aware of the the realities of live performance, at least from the perspective of the performers and producers. Recorded music can be dangerous as it can train people to prefer high-gloss production value over the raw, unvarnished verve of live music.Lastly, I will point out an irony. You felt personally attacked by comments that were at the very least, not intended to be personal. While I acknowledge that you certainly did not intend to make it personal, any of the artists shown here who might read your comments will, at the very least, have to swallow hard for a moment if they read your comment, if not take it personally.In short, your tastes and opinions are valid. But your particular choice of criticism may not be.﻿

author: @MikeEnRegalia
processed_text: ***** You still assume that because my opinion is so radically different from the mainstream I don't know what I'm talking about. I used to play the guitar and sing in a band, and I know the problems of performing live in improvised environments all too well.But I also know that accurate feedback is extremely important for any artist, and i'm sure that artists who have come as far as being featured in a talks at google video, they know how to take it. BTW: I'm a huge fan of Gershwin, and Rhapsody in Blue is one of my 10 most favorite musical compositions of all time. That's also why I was so shocked to see Porgy and Bess performed in this cold, passionless way that's so distant from the spirit of jazz as pluto is from the sun. I have a lot of sympathy for the performers in the video, and my criticism is mainly targeted at the style - I am convinced that if they were to forget about the rules of classical music for a moment and interpret the music without those confinements, it would be so much better ...﻿

author: @redy2meet
processed_text: I enjoyed listening to this video, its more open-minded than many others I've listened to on diets, etc..  My personal experience with eating is, everything in moderation. I have done this for years, and I'm in good health, and look amazingly young for my age. I do prefer alot of salads, fruits, and vegetables, but do eat some fast food, and  at hometown buffet weekly. I like food more, in its original state. I take no vitamin supplements or medications, other than ocassional pot once or twice a month. I don't smoke cigarettes anymore.. quit 30 yrs ago. and drink some wine ocassionally. And like a variety of foods, and ocassionaly dark chocolate.  I do whole grains,prefer the taste of brown rice, and eat wheat, love corn and potatoes in all forms. Eat dairy, low fat milk cheese, love eggs, and seeds, and all types of nuts.  My weight is the same as when I was 16 yrs old, and I am 74 yrs old now, and can easily pass for 45.  I have never had face surgery, or any face fillers nothing. I don't do the gym, I do gardening and a few Isometric type exercises using my body weight, and hand mow my lawns front and back. The biggest key to my looking and feeling so good is I enjoy eating whatever I'm eating and doing, or else I don't eat it or do it, and I love variety with everything. I am never bored then.Or addictive to one-type food. One last thing, if I am out eating with friends at a restaurant and their is something I normally don't care for eating, I simply give myself absolution to eat it without any side effects, therefore I don't have any guilt with eating this type of food. So' its giving myself permissipn to eat it without fear attracting a negative experience back..I do this also with everything quietly, most people would not understand, so I don't discuss this  normally.  Its good to see many people are waking up and taking charge of their life, and physical body and connecting with themself on a Higher level of being.. I apply this way of thinking with everything I do, and this is why I believe l ook the way I do. I follow my inner guidance always.. peace  & love  :)

author: @MoerreNoseshine
processed_text: Great insight (or theory) starting at ca. 40 min: Listening to lossy audio may actually be WORK for the brain. While it DOES throw away the parts that a lossy encoder also throws away, it EXPECTS it, so if it's not there in the audio it fills in those parts. I had myself come to similar ideas about video encoding a long time ago. The point is that our playback mechanisms are BEFORE the brain's filters, so at that point the stuff about to be thrown away is still expected.

Hate to crush a dream but that world is still out of reach.

author: @finfan7
processed_text:
So who gets this UBI?
If it's everyone, the task of setting up structures that would allow this is a century(s) long task in a world where you can somehow get every living person to focus on the task.
If it's just a specific area how do you justify the location?  And any location (for instance a small country like Netherlands) it's still decades before any benefit is felt.  
A small community could probably be built within our lifetime but only with a large amount of input from residents.

author: @_mr3_
processed_text: I'm not sure why you think you're entitled to make a claim like "she's not scientifically trained". She's a physician. There's a term for non-scientific facts: "undiscovered". Fact does not require science to prove it. Science's mechanisms allow it to grow bodies of knowledge, which inherently means its knowledge is not complete. More, it's impossible for science to disprove all of "alternative medicine".  Implying that "alternative medicine" has either not been proven or disproven is incorrect.

author: @Fordi
processed_text:
True enough - but oil only works because it's banked solar energy via ancient life.

Thing is, the earth receives about 180 PW of solar influx (1 kW/m^2 * area of the disc of the earth).  Of that, around 60PW fall on land.  Our inefficient capture methods mean that only 200 TW are available to us for all energy destinations.  So for our whole energy needs (15 TW), we'd need to cover over 7.5% of our land with solar energy capture - around 4 million square miles, or close to the size of the US.

processed_text:

author: @socint74
processed_text: Why are  assertions  related  to free will not prefaced by what, precisely, the speaker means by "free" and "will".  "Freedom" requires  the absence of restraint  or constraints and "Will"  refers  to desires  intentions or decisions . We are free to formulate an intention( i.e. decide) in order to satisfy a desire.It is self evident that  intention frequently may not follow by the action  required to achieve it. processed_text: Yeah, I kind of agree with you, although to be fair it wasn't really the point of his talk, and he has gone into the issue ad nauseum elsewhere, so I can cope with him being a bit flippant about it here.  I think the issue - which he kind of touches on in his response - is that the term "free will" is basically an incoherent concept.  Personally, I think we need to deconstruct that idea and replace it with a functioning alternative, rather than pretending it still works because we want it to...

author: @MakeshiftEstablished
processed_text: And Dennet is simply wrong about patent and copyright law. It should not be based on the utility/function of the thing in question. That leaves far too much room for abuse of the system as we see with Apple. I think that if your invention or idea gets to the point that someone can copy it from the source material with resources of their own then it should be fair game period. Once it's been released into the world, you no longer have control of it and it's the peak of hubris to think you do.

author: @MakeshiftEstablished
processed_text: Daniel Dennet doesn't quite realize or at least state in his original talk that the free will he's talking about is NOT the free will that most people believe they have. He does a disservice to his argument by not clearly mentioning this the first time. For it to have to be coaxed out of him by the questions at the end is annoying. And his argument on punishment barely gets it's needed caveat.

author: @Canaanabolaanan
processed_text:
Thermostats are not sentient. That's saying that all chemical and physical reactions and the reagents involved are sentient, because they are responding to various conditions, and so they "feel." 

I feel your arguments are seriously misguided, and at this point, I think you're just trolling. I am done. Enjoy your weird land of thoughts.

author: @Canaanabolaanan
processed_text: No, because nervous tissue is not a brain. You don't have a brain in your hand. Chicken has water in it. So does Pepsi. The similarities do not make them the same.

author: @JohnOhno
processed_text:
Your hand contains nervous tissue, just as your brain does. If physical substrate is the origin of consciousness, doesn't that imply that your hand has consciousness (only in a smaller way than your brain)?

I also disagree with the idea that your thoughts don't have families. Your thoughts may not have a human-style social structure, but ants and e coli have families. This model of thinking is called memetics, and it is well-known.

author: @JohnOhno
processed_text: Furthermore, who is this 'we'? Is not 'I' an idea that we use to represent whatever idea happens to be talking through us at the moment? That's the model presented in Minsky's Society of Mind, and elsewhere. Even if we require some physical substrate, interpretation is not performed simply by the physical substrate but instead by patterns exhibited by the substrate. Disordered doped silicon, like scrambled brain, is inert.

author: @JohnOhno
processed_text: I do consider sentience and consciousness distinct, because sentience is not a hard problem (at least, not unless you mystify it by invoking qualia). Thermostats are sentient, in the sense that they sense and adjust their internal state in response to their senses. If they had a representation of their internal state (including that representation itself) and could enter an infinite regress, they would be sapient... and MAYBE conscious.

author: @JohnOhno
processed_text: If there is no such thing as a physical substrate (and it's simulations all the way down), I don't see why that should impact my capacity to believe myself sentient or sapient. I see no reason to privilege physics over other internally consistent systems of determining causal paths, nor do I privilege matter over something that merely is indistinguishable from matter. After all, I wouldn't be able to tell.

author: @JohnOhno
processed_text: That's akin to saying that (for instance) the discovery of large prime numbers is not a property of the sieve of eristophanes, but is instead a property of doped silicon. It also implies that if we are unknowingly the product of a simulation, we cannot possibly be sentient or sapient. Both arguments seem to be manufacturing unnecessary and inconvenient divisions for the sake of the defense of the notion of authenticity.

author: @Canaanabolaanan
processed_text: The brain. No brain, no self awareness. My hand is not self-aware in an isolated system. If I formulate a thought, that thought does not carry on a life of its own from then on. It does not raise thought offspring and have a thought-family and go to thought-lawyer school and hangout on the weekends with its thought buddies. Nor does the number sevenlyninthing, even though I just thought of it, and it is now a thought.

author: @Canaanabolaanan
processed_text:
Right. Sentience and sapience are distinct. I don't think sentience and consciousness are though. 

Re:reality-based. I guess you could argue that a mechanical robot in a story is sentient, and with regard to the story, that's true. But in the real world, there are no sentient or conscious ideas. They are imaginings that have no biological -or physical- structures that lend them the ability to be aware. 

Ideas do not interact with each other on their own. We interpret their interaction.

author: @JohnOhno
processed_text:
If ideas cannot be self-aware, then where does self-awareness come from? What part of our mind is self-aware but not constructed out of ideas?
Alternately, if self-awareness is an idea, and other ideas leverage that idea as a tool for reacting to their own structure, how does that differ from the ideas being self-aware without a separate component?
These questions are trivial and are left as an exercise for the reader :-)

author: @JohnOhno
processed_text: I am not challenging the idea that not all conscious creatures are sentient. Sentience is necessary but not sufficient for sapience. However, sentience does not have to be reality-based for it to count as sentience. Ideas, in their own purely simulated arena, interact with each other and with sensory information. Saying that ideas cannot be sentient is like saying that watching television isn't a form of seeing.

author: @Canaanabolaanan
processed_text:
Well, you said ideas HAVE consciousness. That they are themselves conscious. This means they are aware and can experience the world and are sentient. 

And I wasn't saying that consciousness is exclusively sentient - your "if feelings are all you have" rebuttal wasn't a claim I made. 

Ideas are not sentient. So whether consciousness is an idea or an innate process, ideas are not it. 

And if you're challenging the idea that not all conscious creatures are sentient, I'm open to the counter ex.

author: @JohnOhno
processed_text: However, I don't see how consciousness relates to feelings. If feelings are all you have, you aren't sapient -- you are merely sentient (and that's easy; unless you subscribe to the chinese room interpretation, or have a belief in the validity of qualia, or subscribe to the idea of philosophical zombies, then plenty of simple systems are sentient but not sapient in the sense that they feel without second order self-awareness).

author: @JohnOhno
processed_text: Either consciousness is an idea (distinct from the idea of consciousness, which is a model of a model), or consciousness is something innate. The former is the idea presented by Hofstadter and Dennet in The Mind's I, and by Hofstadter in I Am A Strange Loop (or rather, the idea that consciousness is a particular kind of idea with particular properties, as opposed to a specific idea). I don't see how the other approach makes sense.

author: @Canaanabolaanan
processed_text: If you're making the argument that ideas are self-aware, have feelings, and can experience things, I think it's safe to say no one knows what you are talking about. If that's as far as you can tell, there's probably not much you can.

author: @JohnOhno
processed_text: Yes, actually. Ideas have consciousness. Nothing else does, so far as I can tell.

author: @Omerath9
processed_text: And not just the latter, it is very important to teach people, especially from an early age, to think and dwell upon their own emotions. One of the biggest problems in today's western culture, especially Anglo-Saxon culture, is the belief that the more detached one is from his emotions, the more intelligent he will be. I believe it's the exact opposite. The dichotomy is not between being "emotive" or "rational", it's between being emotionally balanced or unbalanced. The current state of affairs leads more to emotional imbalance.

author: @mooimeisjes7347
processed_text:
第3条，傅平出生是1958年，当时中国已实行了户籍制度，任何人不得自由迁移居住地，那怕结婚，农村户口的农民跟城市居民结婚，这个农村人的户口也不可以迁移到城市。
如要迁移户口，必须要工作单位同意、街道办事处同意、对方接收你的所在地区的派出所同意，也就是说，当时的中国人要迁移居住地必须要经过重重关卡方可迁移，这个迁移还要是因为工作的需要这个原因才可以，私人理由是不批准的，为什么这么严厉？
因为在当时的中国，粮食是实行配给制，每个居民凭户口证明到当地的粮油店领取每月的粮食，而粮食在当时是紧缺品，所以对户口管制极度严格。
傅平如果只为姑母收养而迁移户口去全国最大的城市上海是难度超高的，但她可以。
为什么说她可以？因为中国小孩7岁上学的，凭户口本到小学报读的，她能在上海上学，说明她的户口已迁到上海了

中国在61年大饥荒之后实行粮食配给制度，成年人每人每月28市斤粮食，20克（二两）食油，全中国人民处在半饥饱中。
傅平的上海妈妈是一位超级主妇，据书中讲，妈妈在街道工厂工作，是全职工作，也就是说妈妈每天下班后回家做八菜一汤及四个前菜，
当时中国人煮食是用一种叫蜂窝煤炉的炉子煮食，靠燃烧一个蜂窝煤来煮八菜一汤及四个前菜，居然可以赶在晚餐前煮好，让一家人吃上晚饭，超人！这还不包括上海妈妈下班后还要去菜市场买菜，当年家里没有冰箱的，上海的夏天气温高达38度，菜与肉不可能提前一，二天时间买的，会发臭，变质的
同时，每人每月20克食油可以每晚炒这么多菜，不知上海妈妈怎样炒菜的呢？

author: @veganath
processed_text:
Over three quarters of governmental subsidies to agriculture go to meat and dairy farming, hence the artificially low costs.
Worldwide, annually, 40% of all harvested grain was fed to animals being raised for slaughter; in the US that figure was 66%.
If we were to eat the crops grown directly the current supply would satiate a global population of humans of approximately 15 Billion, not to mention for our present population that market forces would substantially reduce the price of plant food.

author: @openlc555
processed_text:
True, we don't know what went on behind the scene. 
But let's look at the fact: The band has a lot more to lose immediately, namely the profits and fan base in China. Given their ambition to become "a leading brand" in the Mandarin-speaking market, they simply can't afford it. 
Google, on the other hand,  is big enough to withstand the fall out, if there is one, by announcing a band is from Taiwan. I just can't image Google is demanding the band to hide their "Taiwanese" identity.

author: @openlc555
processed_text:
I can fully appreciate your concern and anxiety over the "Taiwanese" identity.  But without any evidence, it's a bit "rude" to label Google as the reason behind the whole "Chinese band" episode. After all, I think Google is "big" enough not to be itimidated by whomever you have in mind over a band's country of origin. 
Judging by the band's silence during and after the interview, I am afraid you might be in for a disappointment over this argument in the long run. Best luck to you.

author: @PC160
processed_text: False advertising!  Kurzweil NEVER addressed "mind creation", only potential brain modification with additional external memory/processing power.He never confronts consciousness, that fundamental function of living humans that is not empirical, yet undeniably exists.  I believe life itself is the underlying driver of consciousness, not some brain function analagous to computers.  As the hammer has been created as an extension of our arm, so has the computer been created as an extension of our brain.  The hammer is not alive, nor is the computer.The Pinocchio "Blue Fairy moment" stands in the way of "mind creation".  Understanding what life itself is (if possible) is key to "mind creation".Kurzweil is a brilliant inventor and engineer, but non-empirical life science eludes him (or, perhaps more carefully, he dodges that issue).

author: @jackmillan4643
processed_text: I don't understand what you're trying to say, it's not even known what consciousness is or if it really even exists. We are all under the spell of consciousness so I would pertain that it's a real phenomena but no one knows any even theoretical way of proving if an entity is conscious or not without some subjective bias. Mind creation brings free will, identity and consciousness into the conversation and those are very difficult to quantify or even prove exist at all, so I don't think that Kurzweil's eluding anything, he seems very blunt about his predictions.

author: @PC160
processed_text: jack millanWell. I can't speak for you, but I know consciousness exists, and it ain't no spell!"Pertain"?  I don't follow that. However, "difficult to quantify or even prove to exist at all" gets closer to the point I was trying to make.  This is a material science/empirical perspective.  I would expect an engineer to see things from this perspective.  The science of consciousness must operate in a different way, as we are talking about (by definition) a NON-MATERIAL subject.Kurzweil seems really uncomfortable even acknowledging consciousness (watch his reaction when a questioner mentions "deep thinking").I suppose one quality of a conscious entity would be self-actualization. And, as I've said, I believe life is what's key here.Kurzweil's concept of "the singularity" implies that a computer would suddenly become self-aware (what I called the "Blue Fairy moment") because, what, it achieved some "sound barrier" analog, or had "n" parallel processing operations happening and then (from that great cartoon) "a miracle happens"?I don't think so.Hope that helps.Happy Thanksgiving!

author: @dahalofreeek
processed_text: Depends on what you are talking about.  The duty of the performer is to play the piece as the composer wrote it, the performer must at least attempt to play every dynamic and articulation marking written by the composer as well as the rhythms and notes.  However the performer can play the piece with their own phrasing through rubato and having a direction for the phrase generally you would either have a point that the phrase is going to or you just go up and down with the pitch.

author: @dahalofreeek
processed_text: What you say is true for the most part and I also grow tired of these "experts" in musical interpretation, however there are some performances of pieces where the musician ignores what the composer wrote in terms of tempo, articulation and dynamics.  I have not listened to Lang Lang enough to notice him being particularly bad but when you see dynamic markings in the score being consistently ignored by the performer it can get frustrating.  However in the case of rubato it is up to the performer.

It's an amazing time for technology and I agree, in many ways we are living in the future now. I think the next big thing will be the 3D printing revolution but SF never really covered that

author: @ClayMann
processed_text: A.I, robots, space travel, all these things have turned out to be a lot harder than SF writers ever imagined. I don't think there's much reason to mope about it though. All I think they got wrong was the date. There's vast commercial potential in A.I, robots and space travel (projects to mine asteroids are already being planned) so I don't doubt we'll get everything science fiction has promised. It's just going to take longer than SF authors dreamed.

author: @normbear
processed_text: The slide where he shows "what you perceive" vs "what your eye picks up," (15:36) is misleading, because the brain doesn't construct visual perception from one mostly blurry image. Our eyes are constantly moving in saccades, so that the brain receives several center-focused images per second. These are consolidated to form an overall clear view of the scene. Context plays a part, but the brain has more information to work with than the slide suggests.

author: @skurkaandrew
processed_text: Bashing is different than distinguishing, and I'm sorry if you feel like I did the former, as my intent was only to do the latter. It'd be foolish not to acknowledge the differences in objectives that backpackers have -- i.e. the preferred ratio of hiking versus camping -- and the implications that has for  the gear, supplies, and skills they need. You don't see downhill skiers using cross-country ski gear, right? My focus is purely on helping backpackers enjoy their hiking experience more.

author: @skurkaandrew
processed_text: I wish I got paid to walk, or that I had "a ton of sponsorships and ads," as was also suggested. Instead, I've worked really hard, have paid my dues, and have been creative in order to make money off what I love. Specifically, I guide backpacking trips (17 in 2013), give lots of presentations (25-50 per year), and develop content (e.g. my book).

author: @donach9
processed_text: But in any case, you're also missing the point, people originally did most of their transactions with people they knew: they got their flour milled by the miller, their bread baked by the baker, their wheels made by the wheelwright. War, empire & slavery (as DG shows in his book) is what changed that and brought about the 1st coinage systems, but people did have exchange and systems of debt & credit before that and never relied on a "double coincidence of wants".

author: @donach9
processed_text: You're showing your ignorance. The history of money is filled with transferable promissory notes for instance. Indeed to this day that's what  UK banknotes are, a share in the debt of the crown to the Bank of England, all originating from the loan of £1,200,000 to William III (which has never been repaid). That's why they say on them "I promise to pay the bearer".

author: @dlmaniac
processed_text:
Graeber is living in his own dream as he does not understand the five key elements of money: availability, divisibility, stability, recognition and having own value. 

Debt instantly fails the recognition part as the debt I issue to you might not be accepted as being valid by someone else. Debt issued in one village might not be credible in the next village. This is why historically credible money had to be hard money as they (e.g. gold & silver) brought the recognition and trust with them.

author: @donach9
processed_text: I haven't watched this video yet, but in his book he shows convincingly that 'the myth of barter' is just that: there never has been a society where the majority of goods were distributed by a system relying on the 'double coincidence of wants'. Originally there was communism (or if that word offends you, diffuse reciprocity); as exchange systems developed they were systems of debt and credit, coinage came a few millennia later in order that soldiers would have something to use with strangers.

author: @Greglarr
processed_text: Johnson's theory rests on one aspect, which is troubling me. He states that when you commit suicide in limbo, you emerge one dream layer up. He cites the scene with Ariadne and Fischer jumping off the building when all if the kicks are about to go off. This isn't what happens though. Ariadne and Fischer never hit the ground. The point of them jumping is not to die, but to fall. They're creating a kick to wake themselves from the dream. This explains why they only go one layer up. When you have that falling sensation in a dream, you wake up to wherever you were having that dream. It is shown in the film that they both wake up before hitting the ground. There's even a remark that Ariadne makes about needing to create a kick and gravity being the only available tool.This nullifies the point that Cobb could be in Saido's dream at the end when he's with his kids, because that's not where he'd end up if they shot themselves in limbo.

author: @lnplum
processed_text: He actually addresses that: it doesn't matter, because a) a totem can only help you detect when you are in somebody else's dream and b) like the top it's useless because its function is inversed (its behaviour is only unique in his dreams).So even if the ring was his totem, the ring not being there in the "real world" provides no useful information. Think of the issue of false negatives in drug tests: that the result is negative doesn't mean the sample doesn't contain any drugs. Likewise the absence of something that is presumably absent in the real world can't prove he's not a dream, even though the presence of the ring could indicate he's in a dream (of his own or somebody else's).I think the important point is not that it is most likely all a dream (i.e. nobody was awake throughout the course of the story in the first place), but that there is no absolute proof one way or the other, we can only pick up on all of the hints and derive a conclusion from that.In a way this supports one of the early explanations of the ending: it doesn't matter whether the top will fall, it only matters that Cobb doesn't care. Coob's doubt of what is real and what is just a dream is a core element of the movie. If the movie itself is meant to be ambiguous about whether anything in it is "real", that means the audience gets to experience the same doubt as Cobb.Add to that the explanation that the way dreams are fabricated in the movie strongly resembles how movies are made in the real world and you get to the crux of the presentation: just like Cobb (via the dream) "incepted" the idea that they're living in a dream in Mal, Nolan (via the movie) "incepts" the idea that we, the audience, may be living in a dream in us.This is pretty meta, but I think it fits with what Nolan has done with his previous movies: there's the story as it is being narrated in the movie, the (potentially unknowable) story as the characters portrayed in that movie may actually be experiencing it, and the story Nolan wants to tell you through the movie itself.Either Nolan is a great director, or his fans are simply really good at finding deep meaning in his work. Personally, I think the former is the case, but without being Nolan, he's making it impossible to tell -- and I think that, too, is intentional.

author: @tomwillard8777
processed_text:
1 - It is absolutely the critics job to understand a film, because you should only speak of something that you understand.
2 - The film has LAYERS to it's being understood (see what I did there?) On the top layer, it's a nice bank heist psych-thriller
On a deeper level it's a man that is trying to cope with his own sanity and reach his children
On the deepest level it gets you to wonder if this is all a dream.

author: @tomwillard8777
processed_text:
He never says limbo is always the 4th layer, simply that you go to the bottom.
The bottom being one floor below the deepest dream layer, therefore since there are 3 layers, limbo is the 4th.
They enter Limbo because they all die/choose to go there, they get locked in Fischer's sub-conscious because they enter it because Fischer' is dead, it is limbo for Fischer but only a dream for the rest of them.
SO yes, it was limbo and the 4th layer, but if a layer was removed, limbo would move up one.

author: @tomwillard8777
processed_text:
1 - "So you're still doing that" forging, he still gambling and forging chips, whether Cobb realizes that he made them appear or is completely oblivious, which alludes to Cobb not realizing he is still in a dream, because one moment his hands are empty, the next they are there
2 - It's implied that Cobb can forge, but is bad at forging real items,

author: @roo7227
processed_text:

author: @aesopwatkins1914
processed_text: I subscribe to the belief that the best way to solve our problems is to innovate our way out of them. Furthermore it is my belief that legal action only serves as a band-aid solution to problems when no technical solution is immediately realized. Thus understanding that the underlying issue is the money influence within our political system, especially in the realm of campaign finance, my question then becomes what types of technical solutions can create the conditions under which money and its influence over our politicians is no longer relevant?To answer that question I am first inclined to ask another. In the age of information, where we have immediate access to all forms of media ranging from the written word to video representations, and where we have the proportionate ability to immediately distribute those same forms of media just as readily; All for little more than the price of a computer and a video camera. Why is it that the election process, In the hitherto mentioned age of information, requires so much money in the first place? Why is it so expensive to run a campaign?I find this question strikingly hard to answer. I can understand the cost associated with travel, of booking a venue and of buying a few billboards. But all these things seem to me to add up to a total that dwarfs in comparison to the amount of money these candidates accept in campaign contributions. There seems to be some fundamental disconnect, the campaign system is incredibly inefficient, and appears to be corrupting by its very nature.So then the question becomes, how can we implement recent advents of technology into the election process that would dramatically cut the cost of running for office?My answer:Create an open platform (.gov website) for candidates running for office to obtain campaign finance directly from the electorate. Candidates would post their political platform, their credentials, their past voting records, basically all information relevant for the public to make an informed decision. But here in my view is the interesting bit, every dollar contributed through this website can be tracked and represented in some sort of mathematical diagram and compared to the total amount received by the candidate for his/her campaign. If such a system were in place and were socially recognized as the authority in matters relating to a campaign, we would be able to see what groups have financed each politician. you would be able to see some thing like, this politician has received (x) amount of campaign dollars by undisclosed sources and (y) amount of campaign dollars by disclosed sources. From this you would be able to figure out what percentage of the total amount received comes from sources that are open about their motivations, which in essence would be a measure of how much you can trust a specific politician.The beauty in a solution like this is that it requires no reform on a legislative level. All that is required is a consensus be reached by the people to value openness and honesty in our political leaders.It seems to me that such a website if widely adopted by the public would create a platform that enables a politician to voice their ideas and explain their proposed policies for nearly no money at all, effectively restricting the influence money has over campaigns in the first place..........................................................I would greatly appreciate any feedback.

A) Our genetics and B) our epigenetics (the effect of environmental stimuli on the expression of certain genes as we go through life, specifically during the formative years before we reach the age of 24). The often used counter argument (which, admittedly, is something of a platitude) is: 'when did you did you decide do be a heterosexual?'. The point therein is that such aspects of our personality and personal preferences are expressions of deep-rooted constructs that make up our 'self'.

author: @syystomu
processed_text: Mandarin is... an interesting language. There are some really hard bits like the pronunciation and the writing (though for the writing my suggestion is: just start with the super easy ones and learn one per day and it'll be much easier than you think) but it's also in other ways a really easy language. You'd be surprised. The grammar is very simple and the words are short. The actually tricky parts are when you get to the stylistics but by then you should already speak it pretty well.

author: @syystomu
processed_text: But anyway, yeah, languages aren't as hard as they seem. Often the problem is how you try to learn them. We're naturally inclined to communicate and we should try and learn languages as naturally as possible: the best way is by talking and hearing others talk. Watching movies and TV with subtitles is actually a decent start. The point is to trick your brain into realizing that this is something that it actually wants to learn. Make it hear the language in different contexts so it'll get curious.

author: @syystomu
processed_text: And I think he's absolutely right about language. Being a language nerd, I know very well that my biggest problem with learning a new language is always simply letting go of the anxiety over mistakes. I really suck at it so far but at least I know what to fix... I HAVE actually considered trying alcohol but I'm kind of nervous about that because I don't really drink much at all and I don't know how it'd affect me.

author: @syystomu
processed_text: Wow, I couldn't agree more about the universality of humour. I do think there are tendencies that differ from culture to culture, but there's always something unifying underneath it all. And I've found that people tend to be the same in every country, too: you can find the same types everywhere. There are only superficial differencies which you notice first but which fade away once you get to know the culture better.

author: @theR0NIN
processed_text:
The deaf also _don't_ read English that well, more often than not. Their comprehension isn't that high, for the same reasons I already mentioned: English and ASL are different languages. While some deaf people have been through extensive "mainstreaming" education, and may be able to read and write well, they're a minority of the Deaf population.
These are all reasons that I'm required to hire an interpreter whenever I teach our annual Safety training at work, and I have a deaf student. 
YMMV ofc

author: @theR0NIN
processed_text:
Sorry, but I disagree. MANY deaf people don't write English well. It's a "foreign language" to them. The grammar and syntax are different from ASL, and they often don't spell well either. (Spelling isn't used very often in ASL, unless finger-spelling to a low-ability signer, so they simply don't learn it).
This has been my experience, both with my Deaf brother and his friends, and with the Deaf people I know from work and social contacts.
Your claim about their ability to write is way too broad.

author: @theR0NIN
processed_text: In addition, this project is working towards people from different languages being able to communicate with each other-- even when one of them is deaf! It's pretty amazing!

author: @theR0NIN
processed_text:
A Chinese speaker and a Chinese deaf person typing to each other, would be about the same as a Spanish speaker and a Portuguese speaker typing to each other. Sign Language is different than a spoken language. For example, English and American Sign Language each use different grammar than the other.

Also, deaf people may not be able to spell very well (I'd say this is often the case). 

So, typing isn't really the answer.

processed_text: Because this is designed so that you essentially have a monitor/TV as your main viewport (where your crosshair, viewmodel, HUD, etc. are), and then the projections around you is the in-game surroundings. author: @JustinSlick
processed_text: Didn't expect to be impressed by this, but it's actually very cool.  To anyone complaining about the low quality of the graphics--it doesn't matter.  A high percentage of the spatial resolution in your eye is in the fovea, where the eye is focused (i.e. the screen).  The periphery is good at motion detection, and it seems like this is playing into that.  Little flashes and sparkles, coupled with the faint indication that there's a greater world beyond your TV could really help sell the illusion.

author: @jonathanvalle2683
processed_text:
It's not a whole room dedicated to gaming, the video shows a regular room and the images being projected in the wall, furniture, and part of the floor. 

The biggest progress I could see, was the shockwave effect by processing the room's layout and projecting a wobbly effect on top (you definitely can't do that sort of things by shining a projector in a tv. I don't know how practical it is, but it sure looks really cool.

This is a just a proof of concept, I'd like to see where this is going.

author: @kiwiahead
processed_text:
The projector isn't the main part here. There has to be a Kinect-Like device connected to the projector which will detect the deformations of the scanning grid (in the beginning of the video) to know what is around your TV and display the image without distortion. Also this device would be able to detect colors and edges, in order to make these woobly effects in the last part of the video. 

That device (and its software part) _is_ the core of this project, and the true innovating thing.

author: @johnanth
processed_text:
Can't be an Xbox actually. Red Eclipse & STK use OpenGL, and Xboxes (original + 360) only support the DirectX toolchain. Xbox is a Windows Embedded instance anyway.

I should highlight, this makes it a pain in the ass to develop for Microsoft's consoles. But they sell like hotcakes, so we have to downgrade our games. I've actually been a web developer for years, but if you want to promote the advancement of technology, please get a console that support OpenGL instead.

Regards, developers.

author: @noremac7777
processed_text:
Finding the TV would be the first stage of the process; after that it would want to look at the room for colour correction to make images look right over different surfaces.

Assuming the projector is a standard projector, not supplemented by a camera is a touch silly. Probably uses Kinect.

The scan is also used to project a distorted image of the actual room for an immersive recoil/similar effect as seen at ~40 seconds. Money depends on the exact hardware, but calibration/setup is easy enough.

author: @aesthetis
processed_text: The brain is very good at filling in the blanks in your peripheral vision, meaning the surrounding projection doesn't really need to be very good - just hints. As you move your character's field of vision around and objects/angles leave your TV screen and move onto the walls of your room, your brain will still follow them as if they still looked high res and detailed. This is very clever.

processed_text: Because you're not here to see a players skill; you're here to see the tech concept. Slow actions and obvious movements make it really easy to follow whats happening on screen. It's the same for game video reviews, usually the person capturing the footage won't play as they normally would but instead focus more on capturing environments, enemies and features. In this case they weren't trying to capture what was on screen, instead trying to force as much as they could to appear on the projection.

author: @RobStevens64
processed_text:
Disney is doing something very similar to this at their theme parks. They scanned Cinderella's castle and use it as the canvas for an animated show. Since the room has been 3D scanned, they know how to bend the projection to simulate a flat image even on things like the shelving you see on the right.

They can also use it to "paint" those objects, then simulate making them move, similar to how you see the room pulsate in a couple of the shots. That would be a cool effect for a music game.

The furniture is real.

1) Take picture of room.

2) Project picture of room onto room.

3) Add shockwaves to projection.

author: @LukeSummersgill
processed_text: It's just something to get used to in gaming. We're used to staring at some minute rectangle that makes up our screen real-estate, while we'll have to start treating it as we treat looking around in real life. We don't struggle to use peripheral vision to our advantage in real life and we don't struggle to differentiate between concentrating on one thing and just "taking in" what's on our periphery, if you will.

author: @massimodipierro1
processed_text: Clarification: There was a question about speed and I stated Django is faster. This is true for hello world apps because in web2py one cannot switch off some header validation and session handling. On the other side, when using templates, they are faster in web2py then Django. When using databases' the db IO becomes the bottleneck and the two frameworks tend to perform more or less the same. For hello world apps, bottle.py and pure WSGI beat every other framework.

author: @JonathanSundqvist
processed_text:
Join the authors of Two Scoops of Django for a hands-on Django workshop. We’ll build a real, working site from the ground up, using Django 1.6 and Python 2.7/3.3. We’ll cover as much as we can get through, including but not limited to Python and Django setup, project creation, app creation, models, the Django admin UI, views, migrations with South, user image uploads, new user registration, basic forms.

Prerequisites are listed at pydanny . [com] / europython-django-intro . html
